Introduction

This dataset contains audio features of tracks for a certain user from Spotify.

Every Track is labeled in the column target: 1 means the user likes the track. 0 means he doesnt like it.

This could be the learning task of your models.

Every observation corresponds to a track.

There is 16 columns in the dataset. 3 of them describe the track: tracks name, artist, and the target.

The other 13 columns are the audio features of a track: acousticness. danceability. duration_ms. energy. instrumentalness. key. liveness. loudness. mode. speechiness. tempo. time_signature. valence.

Correlation Matrix

Very important visualization to understand features and target correlation. A correlation matrix is a table which displays the correlation coefficients for different variables. The matrix depicts the correlation between all the possible pairs of values in a table. It is a powerful tool to summarize a large dataset and to identify and visualize patterns in the given data. Strong relationship when the coefficent is near -1 or 1 Weak relationship around 0

library(corrplot)
## corrplot 0.90 loaded
M=cor(data)
corrplot(M, method="number")

cor(data[ , colnames(data) !="target"], data$target)

Spliting training and test set

We choose a ratio of 75% to split into a train and test set

library(caTools)
set.seed(123)
split = sample.split(data$target, SplitRatio = 0.75)
training_set = subset(data, split == TRUE)
test_set = subset(data, split == FALSE)

Scaling the data

Machine Learning Models

We tried several models seen during Practical Works sessions in order to find the best accuracy. As it is a classification problem we focused on the best classification models such as : -Random Forest (and bagging) -Trees -Boosting Trees -Logistic Regression We choose to begin with Random Forest known as a powerful and adaptative algorithm.

Accuracy function

function to compute accuracy of the models. % of good predictions.

accuracy = function(pred,test){
  mean(pred == test)
}
library(caret)
## Le chargement a ncessit le package : lattice

loading caret package to compute confusion matrix of the models

Machine Learning Models

We tried several models seen during Practical Works sessions in order to find the best accuracy. As it is a classification problem we focused on the best classification models such as : -Random Forest (and bagging) -Trees -Boosting Trees -Logistic Regression We choose to begin with Random Forest known as a powerful and adaptative algorithm.

Random Forest

Parameters: RF: mtry = number of features square root. Bagging: mtry = number of features-1 We saw a better performance with Random Forest

#-key-time_signature-mode
library(randomForest)
## randomForest 4.6-14
## Type rfNews() to see new features/changes/bug fixes.
## 
## Attachement du package : 'randomForest'
## L'objet suivant est masqu depuis 'package:gridExtra':
## 
##     combine
## L'objet suivant est masqu depuis 'package:ggplot2':
## 
##     margin
modelTestRF = randomForest(target ~ ., data = training_set, mtry = sqrt(14),importance = TRUE, ntrees = 8000)
## Warning in randomForest.default(m, y, ...): The response has five or fewer
## unique values. Are you sure you want to do regression?
predi_test = predict(modelTestRF, newdata = test_set)
predicted_test = ifelse(predi_test> 0.5, 1, 0)
accRF = accuracy(predicted_test, test_set$target)
accRF

GBM

At the beginning we tried to compute the model with n.trees=500,interaction.depth=4,shrinkage=0.01 and we worked to extend the depth of the model through the parameters. We obtained a nice performance with n.trees = 8000, interaction.depth = 10, shrinkage = 0.009

Test on Parameters:

library(gbm)
## Loaded gbm 2.1.8
modelTestGBM = gbm(target ~ ., data = training_set, distribution = "gaussian", 
                   n.trees=500,interaction.depth=4,shrinkage=0.01)

predi_test = predict(modelTestGBM, newdata = test_set)
## Using 500 trees...
predicted_test = ifelse(predi_test> 0.5, 1, 0)
accuracy(predicted_test, test_set$target)
## [1] 0.7648352
#0.7582418

modelTestGBM = gbm(target ~ ., data = training_set, distribution = "gaussian", 
                   n.trees = 8000, interaction.depth = 10, shrinkage = 0.009)

We can see a better performance of the models without scaling the data. This can be explain after looking to the data it is not really appropriate to apply a scaling process because some features are around 1 and 0. It could have be interesting to scale duration and tempo features because those are the only features with a large spread.

Conclusion

We have shown you how to work on a dataset in order to be able to predict here in our case if the Spotify user will like the song or not. We have done several classification methods to have a range of models, in order to take the best model we compared the accuracy of the models. As we have seen in class, boosting is one of the most powerful classification methods. We have chosen this model and we have optimized it by changing the different parameters. We came first during the Hackathon so we can be satisfied with our work but we can still go further to optimize the model taking into account the authors as mentioned in the beginning of this report. This experience was very instructive and challenging for all of us. We would like to thank Mr.Ghassany and Mrs.SLIMANI for the quality of the teaching provided.

data_ToPredict=read.csv('/Users/daniel/Desktop/test.csv')

model = gbm(target ~ ., data = training_set, distribution = "gaussian", n.trees = 8000, interaction.depth = 10, shrinkage = 0.009)

## Using 8000 trees...
